{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tennessee", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Tennessee, United States}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tennessee\n| width           = \n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| map1            = COVID-19 Cases in Tennessee by counties.svg\n| legend1         = Map of cases by county as of April 30\n{{legend|#FFE4A3|1\u20139}}{{legend|#F2A88D|10\u201349}}{{legend|#E57814|50\u201399}}{{legend|#FF0000|100\u2013249}}{{legend|#A81C1B|> 250}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Tennessee]], U.S.\n| first_case      = [[Williamson County, Tennessee|Williamson County]]\n| arrival_date    = March 5, 2020\n| date            = \n| origin          = \n| type            = \n| confirmed_cases = 10,735<ref name=\"Official Tennessee stats\"/>\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = \n| hospitalized_cases = 1,045 (cumulative)<ref name=\"Official Tennessee stats\"/>\n| recovery_cases  = 5,338<ref name=\"Official Tennessee stats\"/>\n| deaths          = 199<ref name=\"Official Tennessee stats\"/>\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://www.tn.gov/health/cedep/ncov.html}}\n}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the U.S. state of [[Tennessee]] on March 5, 2020. As of April 30, 2020, there are 10,735 confirmed cases, 199 deaths, and 5,338 recoveries.<ref name=\"Official Tennessee stats\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.tn.gov/health/cedep/ncov.html|title=Novel Coronavirus|date=April 29, 2020|website=tn.gov|language=en|access-date=April 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n[[File:Spread of COVID-19 Cases in Tennessee.gif|thumb|Animated map of the spread of coronavirus starting March 11]]\n===March===\nOn March 5, the first case of [[COVID-19]] is reported in Tennessee, in [[Williamson County, Tennessee|Williamson County]]. The patient is a 44-year-old adult man and resident of Williamson County who recently flew on a nonstop flight to [[Boston]] through Nashville's airport.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/health/2020/03/05/coronavirus-tennessee-department-health-bill-lee/4962037002/|title=Coronavirus case detected in Tennessee: First patient is quarantined in Williamson County|last=Kelman|first=Brett|last2=Ebert|first2=Joel|website=The Tennessean|language=en|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, Governor [[Bill Lee (politician)|Bill Lee]] issues an executive order declaring a state of emergency until May 11.<ref>[https://publications.tnsosfiles.com/pub/execorders/exec-orders-lee14.pdf Executive Order \u2013 Lee No. 14] Tennessee Secretary of State</ref>\n\nOn March 16, Nashville mayor [[John Cooper (Tennessee politician)|John Cooper]] forces bars to close in Nashville and Davidson County and imposes limitations on restaurants.<ref name=\":12a\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/2020/03/15/coronavirus-tennessee-latest-news-virus-national-emergency/5052035002/|title=Coronavirus in Tennessee latest news: Restaurant restrictions, ACMs delayed and 39 confirmed cases in Tennessee|website=The Tennessean|language=en|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref> Governor Lee asks schools to close by March 20.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tennessee governor urges all schools to close to prevent spread of COVID-19 |url=https://www.wmcactionnews5.com/2020/03/16/tennessee-governor-urges-all-schools-close-prevent-spread-covid-/ |accessdate=April 16, 2020 |work=WMCActionNews5 com}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, Fiona Whelan Prine, wife and manager of [[country folk]] [[singer-songwriter]] [[John Prine]] announces that she has the coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/entertainment/music/2020/03/19/fiona-whelan-prine-wife-john-prine-has-coronavirus/2876152001/|title=Fiona Whelan Prine, manager and wife of John Prine, has coronavirus: 'Please stay at home'|first=Dave|last=Paulson|website=The Tennessean}}</ref> On March 26, John is admitted to the hospital after suffering sudden onset of COVID-19 symptoms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/john-prine-covid-19-symptoms-974909/|title=John Prine Hospitalized With COVID-19 Symptoms: 'His Situation Is Critical'|first1=Daniel|last1=Kreps|date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> On April 7, John dies, while Fiona Whelan Prine announces she has recovered.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/04/07/arts/07reuters-people-john-prine.html|title=Country Folk Singer John Prine Dies at 73 of Coronavirus Complications|date=April 7, 2020|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, the first death is reported in Nashville.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/health/2020/03/20/first-coronavirus-death-tennessee-reported-nashville-davidson-county/2886440001/|title=Nashville health department reports Tennessee's first coronavirus death|first=Emily R.|last=West|website=The Tennessean}}</ref>\n\nOn March 22, the [[University of Tennessee]] reports its first confirmed case of COVID-19. The case involves a staff member and is confirmed by the Knox County Health Department.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utk.edu/coronavirus/updates/first-confirmed-case-of-covid-19-in-our-campus-community|title=First confirmed case of COVID-19 in our campus community|website=The University of Tennessee Knoxville|language=en|access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, Memphis mayor [[Jim Strickland (politician)|Jim Strickland]] and Shelby County mayor [[Lee Harris (politician)|Lee Harris]] issue \"stay at home\" executive orders that take effect for Memphis and Shelby County the following day.<ref name=\"Strickland01\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.commercialappeal.com/story/news/2020/03/23/memphis-mayor-jim-strickland-issues-safer-at-home-executive-order/2898050001/|title=Memphis' 'safer at home' executive order: What is an essential service?|website=The Commercial Appeal|language=en|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, [[Middle Tennessee State University]] confirms an on-campus student tested positive for COVID-19 and is being supported by MTSU Student Health Services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mtsu.edu/coronavirus/archive/post/79/march-26-from-president-mcphee-covid-19-update|title=MARCH 26: From President McPhee: COVID-19 Update|website=Middle Tennessee State University|language=en|access-date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 29, country music artist [[Joe Diffie]] dies in Nashville due to complications from the coronavirus, according to his publicist.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/30/arts/music/joe-diffie-dead-coronavirus.html|title=Joe Diffie, Grammy-Winning Country Music Star, Dies at 61|last=Caramanica|first=Jon|date=March 30, 2020|website=The New York Times|language=en|accessdate=April 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===April===\nOn April 2, Governor Lee issues a \"stay at home\" executive order for the entire state, effective through April 14.<ref>{{cite news |title=Gov. Bill Lee issues stay-at-home order through April 14 |url=https://communityimpact.com/nashville/franklin-brentwood/coronavirus/2020/03/30/gov-bill-lee-issues-statewide-stay-at-home-order-for-tennesseans/ |accessdate=April 16, 2020 |work=Community Impact Newspaper |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 13, Governor Lee extends the statewide \"stay at home\" executive order through April 30.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tennessee Gov. Bill Lee extends stay at home order through end of April |url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/politics/2020/04/13/tennessee-gov-bill-lee-extends-stay-home-order-through-end-april/2982579001/ |accessdate=April 16, 2020 |work=Tennessean |date=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 15, Governor Lee recommends that all Tennessee schools close for the rest of the 2019\u20132020 school year.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tennessee schools close at governor\u2019s request while state battles coronavirus |url=https://www.wmcactionnews5.com/2020/04/15/gov-lee-closes-all-tennessee-schools-remainder-school-year/ |accessdate=April 16, 2020 |work=WMCActionNews5 com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Governor recommends closing Tennessee schools for the rest of the academic year |url=https://clarksvillenow.com/local/governor-recommends-closing-tennessee-schools-for-the-rest-of-the-academic-year/ |work=ClarksvilleNow.com}}</ref>\n\nOn April 20, 150 inmates test positive for COVID-19 at the [[Bledsoe County Correctional Complex]] in [[Pikeville, Tennessee|Pikeville]], a number that quickly rises as more test positive over the next days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newschannel5.com/news/150-inmates-at-bledsoe-county-correctional-facility-test-positive-for-covid-19-this-weekend|title=150 inmates at Bledsoe County Correctional Facility test positive for COVID-19 this weekend|date=April 20, 2020|website=WTVF|language=en|access-date=April 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://1057news.com/2020/04/23/12/28/35/tdoc-update-345-cases-of-covid-19-now-reported-at-bledsoe-county-correctional-complex/|title=TDOC Update: 345 Cases of COVID-19 Now Reported at Bledsoe County Correctional Complex|last=|first=|date=|website=1057news.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 23, 2020}}</ref> \n\nGovernor Lee confirmed the \"stay at home\" executive order will expire on April 30, and the majority of businesses will be able to reopen the following day, May 1.<ref>{{cite news |title=Governor Lee: TN \u2018Safer at Home\u2019 order to expire April 30, phased reopening next week |url=https://www.wkrn.com/community/health/coronavirus/governor-lee-tn-safer-at-home-order-to-expire-april-30-phased-reopening-next-week/ |accessdate=April 20, 2020 |work=WKRN |date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Government response==\n[[File:Springfield TN Kroger's during the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic.jpg|thumb|A half-empty shelf in the laundry detergent aisle at [[Kroger]] in [[Springfield, Tennessee|Springfield]].]]\n\nOn March 5, Governor [[Bill Lee (Tennessee politician)|Bill Lee]] reported the state's first case: a man in his 40s in [[Williamson County, Tennessee|Williamson County]] who had recently traveled outside the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newschannel5.com/news/gov-bill-lee-tennessee-health-department-to-hold-press-conference-on-coronavirus|title=Gov. Bill Lee announces first confirmed case of coronavirus in Williamson County|last=Bowles|first=Laken|date=March 5, 2020|publisher=[[WTVF]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305211436/https://www.newschannel5.com/news/gov-bill-lee-tennessee-health-department-to-hold-press-conference-on-coronavirus|archive-date=March 5, 2020|access-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, Governor Lee issued Executive Order No. 14 to declare a State of Emergency until it expires on May 11.  The order allows pharmacists to dispense an additional 30-day prescription provided it is to prevent the spread of the virus, allows for alternate COVID-19 testing sites provided that the Tennessee Medical Laboratory Board is notified, restricts an [[Price gouging|excessive price increase]] of items and services until March 27, suspends maximum size limitations for vehicles participating in preventing the spread of the virus, and gives the Tennessee Commissioner of Human Services the ability to waive child care requirements as needed.<ref>[https://publications.tnsosfiles.com/pub/execorders/exec-orders-lee14.pdf Executive Order \u2013 Lee No. 14] Tennessee Secretary of State</ref>\n\n[[File:Long line at grocery store in Smyrna.jpg|thumb|A long line of customers at [[Publix]] in [[Smyrna, Tennessee|Smyrna]].]]\n\nOn March 13, the [[Tennessee Supreme Court]] under Chief Justice [[Jeffrey S. Bivins|Jeff Bivins]] issued a State of Emergency order applying to the Tennessee judicial branch.  The order suspended in-person proceedings until March 31, and extended statutes of limitations and orders of protection that would expire on April 5 or before to April 6.<ref>Laken Bowles [https://www.newschannel5.com/news/tennessee-supreme-court-will-keep-courts-open-suspend-in-person-proceedings-amid-covid-19-concerns Tennessee Supreme Court will keep courts open, suspend in-person proceedings amid COVID-19 concerns] March 13, 2020 [[WTVF]]</ref> Additionally, Governor Lee banned traveling be state employees for non-essential government business, while also banning visitors and tours in Nashville.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kruesi |first1=Kimberlee |title=Lee closes Capitol, halts state travel over coronavirus |url=https://apnews.com/e5377df0a45885f905c52460e98fce09 |website=www.apnews.com |publisher=Associated Press |accessdate=April 6, 2020 |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> The [[Tennessee General Assembly]] also banned the public from the [[Cordell Hull State Office Building|legislative Cordell Hull Office complex]] with only members, staff, and media allowed.<ref>[https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/politics/2020/03/13/tennessee-capitol-closes-public-over-coronavirus-legislature-not-adjourn/5047459002/ Tennessee Capitol, legislative office building close to public amid coronavirus concerns] ''The Tennessean''</ref>\n\nOn March 16, Nashville mayor [[John Cooper (Tennessee politician)|John Cooper]] announced that bars will close across the county and imposed limitations on restaurants.<ref name=\":12a\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/2020/03/15/coronavirus-tennessee-latest-news-virus-national-emergency/5052035002/|title=Coronavirus in Tennessee latest news: Restaurant restrictions, ACMs delayed and 39 confirmed cases in Tennessee|website=The Tennessean|language=en|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref> On the same day, Governor [[Bill Lee (Tennessee politician)|Bill Lee]] asked schools to close by March 20;<ref>{{cite news |title=Tennessee governor urges all schools to close to prevent spread of COVID-19 |url=https://www.wmcactionnews5.com/2020/03/16/tennessee-governor-urges-all-schools-close-prevent-spread-covid-/ |accessdate=April 16, 2020 |work=WMCActionNews5 com}}</ref> on April 15, he recommended they stay closed through the end of the school year.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tennessee schools close at governor\u2019s request while state battles coronavirus |url=https://www.wmcactionnews5.com/2020/04/15/gov-lee-closes-all-tennessee-schools-remainder-school-year/ |accessdate=April 16, 2020 |work=WMCActionNews5 com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Governor recommends closing Tennessee schools for the rest of the academic year |url=https://clarksvillenow.com/local/governor-recommends-closing-tennessee-schools-for-the-rest-of-the-academic-year/ |work=ClarksvilleNow.com}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, Memphis mayor [[Jim Strickland (politician)|Jim Strickland]] and Shelby County mayor [[Lee Harris (politician)|Lee Harris]] issued executive orders to take effect 6:00&nbsp;PM, March 24, requiring residents to remain at home unless they serve essential services.<ref name=\"Strickland01\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.commercialappeal.com/story/news/2020/03/23/memphis-mayor-jim-strickland-issues-safer-at-home-executive-order/2898050001/|title=Memphis' 'safer at home' executive order: What is an essential service?|website=The Commercial Appeal|language=en|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref>  The list of essential services is broad.<ref name=\"Strickland02\">{{Cite web|url=https://covid19.memphistn.gov/listing-of-essential-and-nonessential-services-3-23/|title=Listing of Essential and Nonessential Services |website=City of Memphis|language=en|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe state has gradually collected more information in its coronavirus reporting. Initially, Tennessee was unable to reveal the counties where infected victims lived. On March 10, the state government began reporting coronavirus cases by county, but it still did not have information regarding age and gender. Currently, age, gender, race, and county information is published daily. On March 31, the state government was able to reveal the number of negative cases in each county. Governor Lee also signed an executive order allowing local governments to meet remotely after the legislature failed to do so.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kruesi |first1=Kimberlee |title=Tennessee grapples with what to disclose amid virus outbreak |url=https://apnews.com/5f9bab21e90c5a6c0c6324c5fdc2fe9b |website=apnews.com |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |accessdate=April 3, 2020 |date=April 1, 2020 |quote=Lee has also had to take executive action to let local counties and cities meet remotely after the GOP-dominant Legislature failed to do so in the final hours before abruptly passing an emergency spending plan for the upcoming fiscal year and recessing due to coronavirus concerns.}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, during Governor Lee's daily Covid-19 briefing, Military Commissioner Major General Jeff Holmes announced that 250 members of the [[Tennessee National Guard]] had been mobilized to assist in the state's response and were receiving training in [[Smyrna, Tennessee|Smyrna]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wkrn.com/community/health/coronavirus/governor-lee-addresses-military-assistance-abortion-in-wednesday-covid-19-press-briefing/ |title=Governor Lee addresses military assistance, abortion in Wednesday COVID-19 press briefing |last=McGee |first=Nikki |date=25 March 2020 |website= |publisher=[[WKRN-TV]] |access-date=28 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref> Small teams of Guardsmen were dispersed across 35 counties to support coronavirus testing.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.murfreesboropost.com/news/smyrna-based-guard-team-assists-in-virus-testing/article_73607494-78e1-11ea-aa6d-4328ecb36ee9.html |title=Smyrna-based Guard team assists in virus testing |last=Epright |first=Dan |date=7 April 2020 |website= |publisher=Murfreesboro Post |access-date=28 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref> Members of the [[Tennessee State Guard]] were activated to assist the National Guard's mission.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fox17.com/news/local/tennessee-state-guard-members-volunteer-in-fight-against-covid-19-04-08-2020 |title=Tennessee State Guard members volunteer in fight against COVID-19 |last=Jorge |first=Kaylin |date=8 April 2020 |website= |publisher=[[WZTV]] |access-date=28 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nOn April 2, Governor Lee announced that he would sign Executive Order No. 23, which would call for all residents to stay home through April 14, unless they are carrying out essential activities.<ref>{{cite news |title=Gov. Bill Lee issues stay-at-home order through April 14 |url=https://communityimpact.com/nashville/franklin-brentwood/coronavirus/2020/03/30/gov-bill-lee-issues-statewide-stay-at-home-order-for-tennesseans/ |accessdate=April 16, 2020 |work=Community Impact Newspaper |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> On April 13, Governor Lee extended the order to the end of the month, to align with [[Donald Trump|President Trump's]] plans for businesses to reopen in early May.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tennessee Gov. Bill Lee extends stay at home order through end of April |url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/politics/2020/04/13/tennessee-gov-bill-lee-extends-stay-home-order-through-end-april/2982579001/ |accessdate=April 16, 2020 |work=Tennessean |date=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Tennessee Major Metros Economic Restart Task Force was established on April 16, composed of mayors representing Knoxville, Memphis, Nashville, and Chattanooga, as well as business and health leaders. The task force will plan resumption of business suspended due to COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tennessee metro mayors form economic restart task force |url=https://www.wate.com/news/tennessee/tennesse-metro-mayors-form-economic-restart-task-force/ |accessdate=April 27, 2020 |work=WATE |date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nGovernor Lee announced on April 20 that the 'Safer at Home' order would expire on April 30, and the majority of businesses would be able to reopen the following day, May 1.<ref>{{cite news |title=Governor Lee: TN \u2018Safer at Home\u2019 order to expire April 30, phased reopening next week |url=https://www.wkrn.com/community/health/coronavirus/governor-lee-tn-safer-at-home-order-to-expire-april-30-phased-reopening-next-week/ |accessdate=April 20, 2020 |work=WKRN |date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impact on sports==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\nOn March 12, the [[National Basketball Association]] announced the season would be suspended for 30 days, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Memphis Grizzlies season|Memphis Grizzlies]].<ref name=nba>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |title=Silver: NBA hiatus likely to last 'at least' 30 days |date=March 12, 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>  In the [[National Hockey League]], the season was suspended for an indefinite amount of time, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Nashville Predators season|Nashville Predators]].<ref name=nhl>[https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 NHL statement on coronavirus] NHL, March 12, 2020</ref> The [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] cancelled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref name=ncaa>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>[https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak] MLive.com, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n{{stack|clear=right|{{2020 coronavirus pandemic data/Tennessee medical cases by county}}}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Tennessee medical cases chart}}\n\n===Confirmed cases by date===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\" style=\"text-align:left\"\n! colspan=\"3\" |2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) Cases in Tennessee<ref name=\"Official Tennessee stats\"/><br />\n|-\n! Date !! Cases !! Total Deaths\n|-\n|Apr 30\n|10735\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|199\n|-\n|Apr 29\n|10366\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|195\n|-\n|Apr 28\n|10052\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|188\n|-\n|Apr 27\n|9918\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|184\n|-\n|Apr 26\n|9667\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|181\n|-\n|Apr 25\n|9189\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|179\n|-\n|Apr 24\n|8726\n|168\n|-\n|Apr 23\n|8266\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|170\n|-\n|Apr 22\n|7842\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|166\n|-\n|Apr 21\n|7394\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|157\n|-\n|Apr 20\n|7238\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|152\n|-\n|Apr 19\n|7070\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|148\n|-\n|Apr 18\n|6762\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|145\n|-\n|Apr 17\n|6589\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|142\n|-\n|Apr 16\n|6262\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|141\n|-\n|Apr 15\n|6079\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|135\n|-\n|Apr 14\n|5823\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|124\n|-\n|Apr 13\n|5610\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|109\n|-\n|Apr 12\n|5308\n|101\n|-\n|Apr 11\n|5114\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|101\n|-\n|Apr 10\n|4862\n|style=\